### forwardRef

`forwardRef` lets your component expose a DOM node to a parent component using a ref. It passes the ref through to a child element.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { forwardRef } from 'react';

const MyInput = forwardRef(function MyInput(props, ref) {
  return <input ref={ref} {...props} />;
});
```

### Usage in Parent

```jsx
function Form() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const focusInput = () => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  };

  return (
    <>
      <MyInput ref={inputRef} placeholder="Type here" />
      <button onClick={focusInput}>Focus Input</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

### Exposing Custom Handles with useImperativeHandle

```jsx
import { forwardRef, useImperativeHandle, useRef } from 'react';

const CustomInput = forwardRef(function CustomInput(props, ref) {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  useImperativeHandle(ref, () => ({
    focus: () => inputRef.current.focus(),
    clear: () => { inputRef.current.value = ''; },
    scrollToView: () => inputRef.current.scrollIntoView()
  }), []);

  return <input ref={inputRef} {...props} />;
});

// Parent usage
<inputRef.current.focus(); />
<inputRef.current.clear(); />
```

| Concept | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| forwardRef | Passes ref through to a child |
| useImperativeHandle | Customizes the exposed ref value |
| Ref forwarding | Essential for reusable component libraries |

### Common Use Cases

- Reusable input components
- Third-party library integration
- Animation libraries requiring DOM access
- Focus management in forms

> **Key Point:** forwardRef is primarily used in reusable component libraries. For app-internal components, consider whether a declarative approach (props for focus, state for values) could work instead.

codeExample:
import { forwardRef } from 'react';

const FancyButton = forwardRef(function FancyButton({ children, ...props }, ref) {
  return (
    <button ref={ref} className="fancy-btn" {...props}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
});

export default FancyButton;
